sis. If an analyst naively compares the unadjusted $634 pre-split secondary price to the S-1\'s EPS of $(1.69) for FY2025, the implied P/E multiple would appear absurdly distorted. The correct comparison requires dividing the $634 pre-split price by 5 to arrive at **$126.80**, which is then comparable to the S-1\'s post-split EPS, book value per share, and other per-share metrics.\n\n### 2. Avoiding a 5× Valuation Error\nWithout adjustment, an analyst would overstate the price-to-earnings, price-to-book, and price-to-sales-per-share ratios by a factor of exactly 5. For example:\n- **Incorrect:** $634 ÷ $0.01 (FY2024 basic EPS) = 63,400× P/E\n- **Correct:** $126.80 ÷ $0.01 (FY2024 basic EPS) = 12,680× P/E\n\nWhile both multiples are high, the unadjusted figure is mathematically meaningless because the numerator (price) and denominator (EPS) are on different share-count bases.\n\n### 3. Consistency with Pro Forma and Dilution Metrics\nThe S-1\'s pro forma net tangible book value per share, pro forma EPS, and dilution calculations all use post-split share counts. Any valuation framework (DCF per share, comparable-company P/E, price/NTBV) that uses the S-1\'s per-share figures as the denominator must pair them with a split-adjusted price as the numerator.\n\n### 4. Preferred Stock Conversion Economics\nThe preferred stock conversion rate was proportionately adjusted (from 10 to 50 shares per preferred share). Analysts modeling fully diluted share counts or as-converted valuations using the S-1\'s post-split conversion terms must ensure their implied share prices are also on a post-split basis to correctly calculate conversion premiums, ownership percentages, and implied enterprise values.\n\n### 5. Historical Trend Analysis\nBecause the S-1 retroactively adjusts all periods (2023, 2024, 2025, Q1 2025, Q1 2026), any time-series analysis of per-share metrics (e.g., EPS growth trends, book value per share trajectory) is internally consistent on a post-split basis. Introducing unadjusted pre-split market prices into such an analysis would create a structural discontinuity that invalidates trend-based conclusions.\n\n---\n\n**Bottom line:** The split-adjusted equivalent of Forge Global\'s ~$634 pre-split peak is **$126.80 per share**. Every per-share metric in the SpaceX S-1 — EPS, weighted average shares, pro forma EPS, net tangible book value per share, conversion ratios, and outstanding share counts — is presented on a post-split basis. Failure to adjust pre-split secondary market prices by dividing by 5 before comparing them to any S-1 per-share figure will produce a 5× systematic error in all derived valuation multiples.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://forgeglobal.com/spacex_stock",\n      "name": "Forge Global - SpaceX Stock Page"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
